    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Death Row: No Room for Error</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Cy Shain letter on errors in capital cases questions death penalty's deterrent effect and moral justifiability (July 10 James Q Wilson Op-Ed article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What Death-Penalty Errors?'', by James Q. Wilson (Op-Ed, July 10):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What Death-Penalty Errors?'', by James Q. Wilson (Op-Ed, July 10):</p>
        <p>Mr. Wilson's article about the Columbia Law School study that concluded that inept lawyering and legal errors occur in a significant number of death penalty cases seems to treat legal error as if it were inconsequential and at the same time challenges death penalty opponents to prove that truly innocent people have been executed.</p>
        <p>To those of us who believe in the rule of law, that is a highly questionable position to take.</p>
        <p>Since he lays down the gauntlet, I challenge Mr. Wilson to prove that the death penalty has a deterrent effect and is morally justified.</p>
        <p>CY SHAIN  San Francisco, July 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
